nd continuing through the years, ideas, images, behaviors, and attitudes associated with Confucianism have come back into public and private life. In this volume, scholars from a wide range of disciplines explore the contemporary Confucian revival in China, looking at Confucianism and the state, intellectual life, and popular culture. Contributors note how the revival of Confucianism plays out in a variety of ways, from China's relationship with the rest of the world, to views of capitalism and science, to blockbuster movies and teenage fashion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aConfucianismxHistoryx21st centuryxChina. 0aConfucianismzChinaxHistoryy21st century. 4aAsian Studies : Confucianism. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aHistory : History. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aDeBlasi, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster, Robert W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammond, Kenneth J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammond, Kenneth J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoore, Robert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Julia K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOldstone-Moore, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichey, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichey, Jeffrey L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2014z978311149015140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438454931423Coveruhttps://